## ðŸ”¥ OOP IN JAVA â€“ Complete Breakdown (with C++ Comparison)

### ðŸ“Œ OOP stands for:

**Object-Oriented Programming** â€” a paradigm where everything revolves around **objects and classes**.

---

## âœ… 4 Core Pillars of OOP (Java & C++)

| S.No | Concept           | Description                                      |
| ---- | ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| 1    | **Encapsulation** | Binding data and methods in one unit             |
| 2    | **Abstraction**   | Showing essential details, hiding internal logic |
| 3    | **Inheritance**   | Reusing code from parent class                   |
| 4    | **Polymorphism**  | Many forms â€” same method behaves differently     |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 1. **Class & Object** (The Base of OOP)

### âœ… In Java:

```java
class Car {
    String color = "Red";
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car();  // Object creation
        System.out.println(myCar.color); // Red
    }
}
```

### âœ… In C++:

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    string color = "Red";
};

int main() {
    Car myCar;
    cout << myCar.color;
}
```

### ðŸ”„ **Java vs C++**

| Feature         | Java                              | C++                      |
| --------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Memory          | Uses **heap**, managed by **JVM** | Manual memory management |
| Object creation | `new` keyword required            | Can be created directly  |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 2. **Encapsulation** â€“ Hiding data using private access

### âœ… Java Example:

```java
class Student {
    private int marks; // private data

    public void setMarks(int m) {
        marks = m;
    }
    public int getMarks() {
        return marks;
    }
}
```

### âœ… C++ Example:

```cpp
class Student {
private:
    int marks;

public:
    void setMarks(int m) { marks = m; }
    int getMarks() { return marks; }
};
```

### ðŸ”„ Java vs C++:

| Feature          | Java                               | C++         |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------------- | ----------- |
| Getter/Setter    | Preferred using naming conventions | Manual      |
| Access Modifiers | public, private, protected         | Same in C++ |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 3. **Abstraction** â€“ Hiding implementation details

### âœ… Java (via abstract class):

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void makeSound();
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
}
```

### âœ… Java (via interface):

```java
interface Animal {
    void makeSound();
}
class Cat implements Animal {
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Meow");
    }
}
```

### âœ… C++ Example:

```cpp
class Animal {
public:
    virtual void makeSound() = 0; // Pure virtual function
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void makeSound() {
        cout << "Bark";
    }
};
```

### ðŸ”„ Java vs C++:

| Feature             | Java                       | C++                 |
| ------------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------- |
| Abstraction methods | abstract class, interface  | abstract class only |
| Pure virtual method | Not explicitly called that | Yes, via `= 0`      |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 4. **Inheritance** â€“ Acquiring properties from another class

### âœ… Java:

```java
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating");
    }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Barking");
    }
}
```

### âœ… C++:

```cpp
class Animal {
public:
    void eat() {
        cout << "Eating";
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void bark() {
        cout << "Barking";
    }
};
```

### ðŸ”„ Java vs C++:

| Feature              | Java                     | C++                     |
| -------------------- | ------------------------ | ----------------------- |
| Multiple Inheritance | âŒ Not supported directly | âœ… Supported via classes |
| Solved using         | Interfaces               | Virtual base classes    |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 5. **Polymorphism** â€“ One interface, many forms

### ðŸ“Œ Two types:

* **Compile-Time Polymorphism** (Method Overloading)
* **Run-Time Polymorphism** (Method Overriding)

---

### âœ… Overloading (Java):

```java
class Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }
}
```

### âœ… Overloading (C++):

```cpp
class Calculator {
public:
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }
};
```

---

### âœ… Overriding (Java):

```java
class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Animal Sound"); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() { System.out.println("Dog Barks"); }
}
```

### âœ… Overriding (C++):

```cpp
class Animal {
public:
    virtual void sound() {
        cout << "Animal Sound";
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void sound() {
        cout << "Dog Barks";
    }
};
```

---

### ðŸ”„ Java vs C++:

| Feature                 | Java                                | C++                             |
| ----------------------- | ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Function Overloading    | âœ… Yes                               | âœ… Yes                           |
| Function Overriding     | âœ… Yes (`@Override`)                 | âœ… Yes (using `virtual` keyword) |
| Virtual keyword needed? | âŒ No, all methods can be overridden | âœ… Yes for polymorphism          |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 6. **Access Modifiers in OOP**

| Modifier    | Java                                    | C++                           |
| ----------- | --------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| `public`    | Accessible everywhere                   | Same                          |
| `private`   | Accessible in class only                | Same                          |
| `protected` | Accessible in same package & subclasses | Accessible in derived classes |

---

## ðŸ”¶ 7. **Constructor Concept**

### âœ… Java:

```java
class Car {
    Car() {
        System.out.println("Car created");
    }
}
```

### âœ… C++:

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    Car() {
        cout << "Car created";
    }
};
```

| Feature              | Java                         | C++                  |
| -------------------- | ---------------------------- | -------------------- |
| Default Constructor  | Auto-generated               | Auto-generated       |
| Constructor Overload | âœ… Yes                        | âœ… Yes                |
| Destructor           | âŒ No destructor (GC handles) | âœ… Yes, used manually |

---

## ðŸ”¥ BONUS: Java OOP is Strict, C++ is Flexible

| Topic                | Java                          | C++                      |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Memory Management    | Automatic (Garbage Collector) | Manual (`new`, `delete`) |
| Multiple Inheritance | âŒ Not directly supported      | âœ… Fully supported        |
| Operator Overloading | âŒ Not allowed                 | âœ… Supported              |
| Friend Functions     | âŒ Not supported               | âœ… Supported              |
| Structs              | âŒ Not available               | âœ… Available              |

---

## ðŸ Final Summary

| OOP Concept    | Java                                     | C++                               |
| -------------- | ---------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Class & Object | Everything must be inside a class        | Not mandatory                     |
| Inheritance    | Single & multilevel via interfaces       | Full support (including multiple) |
| Polymorphism   | Method Overload & Override               | Function Overload & Virtual       |
| Abstraction    | Abstract class / Interface               | Abstract classes (pure virtual)   |
| Encapsulation  | Achieved using private + setters/getters | Same as Java                      |

